Geocoding and routing

In this demonstration we will experiment with using the ggmap package to geocode addresses and to get travel times and routes between locations.

First, we need to load the ggmap package. ggmap is a powerful interface between R and google maps. More information on what you can do with it can be found here.

library(ggmap)

Here, we will register a Google API key. The is one I set up for this class and it will not last beyond the end of the semester, so I would recomend setting up your own if you need geocoding or routing tools. There are a certain number of free calls per minute and a generous trial perion

register_google(key = YOUR_KEY_HERE)

You are welcome to use these two addresses here in South Bend, or to use your own.

house <- "712 West LaSalle Ave, South Bend IN 46601"
work <- "Hesburgh Library, University of Notre Dame"

Interactive Geocoding

Next, lets try using the geocode funtion to get the latitute and longitude for each of these point.

geocode(house)
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=712+West+LaSalle+Ave,+South+Bend+IN+46601&key=xxx-o9Xyvg
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##     lon   lat
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 -86.3  41.7

You can see that this works by calling the Google Maps API and parsing the results into something R can use.

We have a lot of variables that we can set, most relevantly, we can either use Google’s geocoder or the Data Science Kit with the source variable. In most cases it is better to use google (which is the default)

Probably most useful for you is the “output” variable. The default is to just return the coordinates, but google can also can return a measure of how good the estimate is. This is particularly useful in cases where someone entered the address and there might be errors. So lets try doing it with a bad address

geocode("100 Obviously Fake Street, South Bend IN 46617")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=100+Obviously+Fake+Street,+South+Bend+IN+46617&key=xxx-o9Xyvg
## "100 Obviously Fak..." not uniquely geocoded, using "suite 100, 415 e madison st, south bend, in 46617, united states"
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##     lon   lat
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 -86.2  41.7

With the default, this (obviously fake) address yields a normal lat lon pair. So it seems like it worked without a problem

geocode("100 Obviously Fake Street, South Bend IN 46617", output = "latlona")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=100+Obviously+Fake+Street,+South+Bend+IN+46617&key=xxx-o9Xyvg
## "100 Obviously Fak..." not uniquely geocoded, using "suite 100, 415 e madison st, south bend, in 46617, united states"
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##     lon   lat address                                                      
##   <dbl> <dbl> <chr>                                                        
## 1 -86.2  41.7 suite 100, 415 e madison st, south bend, in 46617, united st~

Using output = “latlona” we can see what address the geocoder found. In this case, just the name of the city

geocode("100 Obviously Fake Street, South Bend IN 46617", output = "more")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=100+Obviously+Fake+Street,+South+Bend+IN+46617&key=xxx-o9Xyvg
## "100 Obviously Fak..." not uniquely geocoded, using "suite 100, 415 e madison st, south bend, in 46617, united states"
## # A tibble: 1 x 9
##     lon   lat type    loctype address               north south  east  west
##   <dbl> <dbl> <chr>   <chr>   <chr>                 <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 -86.2  41.7 establ~ rooftop suite 100, 415 e mad~  41.7  41.7 -86.2 -86.2

With output = “more” or output = “all” we get a measure of how accurate the geocoding was (in this case type = postal_code and loctype = approximate) indicating that it was not very accurate. It would now be easy to filter these results.

A very common problem with batch geocoding lots of addresses is data scientists not taking into account the accuracy of the geocoding. This can result in all of the failed geocodes ending up in the same area and can very strongly affect the distribution of something.

Batch Geocoding

The Gecode function can also take a vector of addresses with little trouble. To experiment with this, we will create a dataframe with addresses. For part of your assignment this week, you will need to load a csv. Next, we can run the geocode command over the whole list as long as it is a character vector.

address.df <- data.frame(address = c("712 West LaSalle Ave, South Bend IN 46601", "Hesburgh Library, University of Notre Dame", "Notre Dame Stadium", "1047 Lincoln Way E South Bend, IN 46601","227 W Jefferson Blvd South Bend, IN 46601"),id = c(1:5))

geocoded.list <- geocode(as.character(address.df$address), output = "more")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=712+West+LaSalle+Ave,+South+Bend+IN+46601&key=xxx-o9Xyvg

address.all <- cbind(address.df, geocoded.list[,c(1:3)])

Sometimes you will run into problems with the google geocoding api returning “geocode failed with status OVER_QUERY_LIMIT” even when you running the geocodeQueryCheck() command shows you have not exhausted your available queries. This is often because you are sending too many queries (or someone else on your domain) per second to the Google API. There are two main workarounds. The first is to update your version of ggmap. This will allow you set a Google API key and prevents problems from others overdoing the available queries. Second, you can iterate through manually and geocode each address in the data frame, pausing for a few seconds if it fails.

for(i in 1:nrow(address.df)){
  result <- geocode(as.character(address.df$address[i]), output = "latlona", source = "google")
  while(is.na(result[1])){ #checks if the latitude is NA and reruns if it is
    Sys.sleep(2) #Pauses for a minute to let the API Catch up
    result <- geocode(as.character(address.df$address[i]), output = "latlona", source = "google")
  } 
  address.df$lon[i] <- as.numeric(result[1])
  address.df$lat[i] <- as.numeric(result[2])
  address.df$geoAddress[i] <- as.character(result[3])
}
head(address.df)
##                                      address id       lon      lat

This is a brute force way of doing it. As the code currently is, what do you think would happen if it encountered an address it could not find?

If you this approach in your assignment, you may want to ensure that it does not run indefinitely.

Routing

We can also get a distance (and travel time) between them using the mapdist function

mapdist(from = house, to = work)
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/distancematrix/json?origins=712+West+LaSalle+Ave,+South+Bend+IN+46601&destinations=Hesburgh+Library,+University+of+Notre+Dame&key=xxx-o9Xyvg&mode=driving
## # A tibble: 1 x 9
##   from          to                m    km miles seconds minutes hours mode 
##   <chr>         <chr>         <int> <dbl> <dbl>   <int>   <dbl> <dbl> <chr>
## 1 712 West LaS~ Hesburgh Lib~  6086  6.09  3.78     781    13.0 0.217 driv~

The default is with driving, but we can change it to public transportation, walking, or riding a bicycle using “mode” set to one of (“driving”, “walking”, “bicycling”, “transit”)

mapdist(from = house, to = work, mode = "bicycling")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/distancematrix/json?origins=712+West+LaSalle+Ave,+South+Bend+IN+46601&destinations=Hesburgh+Library,+University+of+Notre+Dame&key=xxx-o9Xyvg&mode=bicycling
## # A tibble: 1 x 9
##   from          to                m    km miles seconds minutes hours mode 
##   <chr>         <chr>         <int> <dbl> <dbl>   <int>   <dbl> <dbl> <chr>
## 1 712 West LaS~ Hesburgh Lib~  4956  4.96  3.08    1034    17.2 0.287 bicy~

We can also create a path that shows the steps between two locations using the route command

towork <- route(from = house, to = work, mode = "bicycling", alternatives = T, structure = "legs")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/directions/json?origin=712+West+LaSalle+Ave,+South+Bend+IN+46601&destination=Hesburgh+Library,+University+of+Notre+Dame&key=xxx-o9Xyvg&mode=bicycling&alternatives=true&units=metric

We can then plot this route with a little it of manipulation in ggmap. First we will use the get_map command to cache basemap tiles from google. Then we will generate lines from the start and end each leg and color them based on the route

southbend <- get_map("leeper park, South Bend, IN", zoom = 14, maptype = "roadmap")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=leeper%20park,%20South%20Bend,%20IN&zoom=14&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=roadmap&language=en-EN&key=xxx-o9Xyvg
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=leeper+park,+South+Bend,+IN&key=xxx-o9Xyvg
ggmap(southbend)+
  geom_leg(aes(x = start_lon, y = start_lat, xend = end_lon, yend = end_lat,colour = route),alpha = .5, size = 2, data = towork)
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_segment).
